```csharp
using System.Runtime.CompilerServices;
using BenchmarkDotNet.Attributes;
using BenchmarkDotNet.Running;

public class Program
{
    static void Main(string[] args)
    {
        BenchmarkRunner.Run<Program>();
    }

    private static int MyReadOnlyProp { get; } = SetupField();

    [MethodImpl(MethodImplOptions.NoInlining)]
    private static int SetupField() => 42;


    [Benchmark]
    [Arguments(100)]
    [MethodImpl(MethodImplOptions.AggressiveOptimization)] // makes code slower
    public double Foo1(int x)
    {
        return x % MyReadOnlyProp;
    }

    [Benchmark]
    [Arguments(100)]
    public double Foo2(int x)
    {
        return x % MyReadOnlyProp;
    }
}

/*

| Method |   x |      Mean |     Error |    StdDev |
|------- |---- |----------:|----------:|----------:|
|   Foo1 | 100 | 1.7387 ns | 0.0106 ns | 0.0082 ns |
|   Foo2 | 100 | 0.4181 ns | 0.0077 ns | 0.0072 ns |

*/
```

In this benchmark `[MethodImpl(MethodImplOptions.AggressiveOptimization)]` actually makes code slower because `Foo2` is promoted from **tier0** to **tier1** naturally and at that point (on ~30th iteration) `MyReadOnlyProp` is basically a constant so JIT can just calculate the result and drop that `%` (see https://github.com/dotnet/coreclr/pull/27079#discussion_r332491591)

>Since Tier1 methods are jitted later they often end up with better codegen, since more classes are initialized, readonly static values are known, etc.

So can we re-JIT methods which were forced to skip tier0 (e.g. methods with loops or with `[MethodImpl(MethodImplOptions.AggressiveOptimization)]`) in such cases? Especially for the methods with loops (`COMPlus_TC_QuickJitForLoops` is `0` by default). 

PS: a vote to enable `COMPlus_TC_QuickJitForLoops` by default 🙂 as it not only improves startup time but also may lead to a better codegen.

cc @benaadams

